					<h4>Environment and Energy Discussion</h4>
		
		<h1>Donald Hodel, Former Interior Secretary, To Visit CU</h1>
		<h2><i></i></h2>
		<div class="text-feature_print">
							<p>By Jenny Shank, 1-17-06</p>
			
							<table width="25" align="right" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">
					<tr>
						<td>&nbsp;</td>
						<td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/thumbnails_feature/hodel_thumb.jpg" class="thumbnail-feature" border="0" align="right" width="150" height="176" /></td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>

					
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>
				</table>
			
							CU Boulder's <a href="http://www.centerwest.org" title="Center of the American West">Center of the American West</a> will bring Donald Hodel to speak on campus on Thursday, January 19 at 6 p.m. in the Eaton Humanities Building (Room 150).  Professors Patricia Limerick and Charles Wilkinson will lead Hodel in a discussion, and a reception will follow. Hodel served in the Regan administration as Secretary of the Interior from 1985 to 1989 and as the Secretary of Energy from 1982 to 1985.  According to the Center's press release, "As interior secretary, Hodel focused on energy issues and pushed to increase domestic energy porduction through the expansion of drilling offshore and in the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge."  But the Center always strives for a non-partisan approach in its presentation, and further notes that "Hodel also supported the restoration of the flooded Hetch Hetchy Valley in Yosemite National Park."  Still, given Boulder's overwhelmingly liberal population, there might be more friendly feelings toward Hodel on stage than in the audience.  
						<b>[End of article]</b>
		</div>

